Step 1: Check Virtualization Support
egrep -c '(vmx|svm)' /proc/cpuinfo

 Output:

>0 → Supported 
0 → Enable VT-x/AMD-V in BIOS 
Step 2: Install KVM & Tools (Ubuntu 22.04)
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y qemu-kvm libvirt-daemon-system libvirt-clients bridge-utils virt-manager
 Step 3: Enable & Start libvirt
sudo systemctl enable libvirtd
sudo systemctl start libvirtd

Check:

sudo systemctl status libvirtd
 Step 4: Add User Permissions
sudo usermod -aG libvirt $USER
sudo usermod -aG kvm $USER
newgrp libvirt
 Step 5: Verify Installation
virsh list --all

 Should not show error.

 Step 6: Create VM (GUI – virt-manager)

Launch:

virt-manager
Steps:
Click Create New VM
Select Local install media (ISO)
Choose OS ISO (Ubuntu/CentOS)
Allocate:
RAM: 2GB+
CPU: 2 cores
Disk: 20GB
Network: default (NAT for now)

 VM will boot and install OS.

 Step 7: Configure Bridge Networking (Important)

 Default network = NAT
 Bridge = VM gets IP from same network as host (real-world scenario)

 Create Bridge (Ubuntu Netplan)

Edit:

sudo nano /etc/netplan/01-netcfg.yaml

Example config:

network:
  version: 2
  renderer: networkd
  ethernets:
    enp0s3:
      dhcp4: no
  bridges:
    br0:
      interfaces: [enp0s3]
      dhcp4: yes

Apply:

sudo netplan apply
 Verify Bridge
ip a

 You should see:

br0
 Attach VM to Bridge

In virt-manager:

Open VM → Settings → Network

Change to:

Bridge br0
 Step 8: virsh Commands (CLI Control)
List VMs
virsh list --all
Start VM
virsh start <vm-name>
Shutdown VM
virsh shutdown <vm-name>
Force Stop
virsh destroy <vm-name>
Autostart VM
virsh autostart <vm-name>
VM Info
virsh dominfo <vm-name>
 Step 9: Test Networking

Inside VM:

ip a

 You should see:

Same subnet as host (if bridge works)

Test:

ping google.com
 Common Issues
 virt-manager not opening
sudo virt-manager
 Permission denied (virsh)
newgrp libvirt
 Bridge not working
Wrong interface name (check with ip a)
NetworkManager conflict
 VM no internet
Check bridge config
Restart libvirt:
sudo systemctl restart libvirtd
 Viva Points
KVM = Kernel-based virtualization
libvirt = management layer
virt-manager = GUI tool
virsh = CLI tool
NAT vs Bridge:
NAT → private network
Bridge → same network as host
